INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6e0dbede-165d-40b9-bc8b-ab1d86854c6a',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Go Modules — Lock Files, Versioning, and Dependency Auditing You Actually Need$escape$,
  $escape$Go modules use `go.mod` to declare dependencies and `go.sum` as a cryptographic lock file — every dependency's hash is recorded, making reproducible builds and supply-chain verification built-in, not bolted on. Unlike npm's `package-lock.json`, `go.sum` stores hashes for both the module zip and its `go.mod`, so even indirect dependencies are verified against the Go checksum database (sum.golang.org).

Use `go mod tidy` to prune unused dependencies and add missing ones — run it before every commit. `go mod verify` checks that on-disk module caches match `go.sum` hashes, catching corruption or tampering. For auditing vulnerabilities, `govulncheck ./...` (from `golang.org/x/vuln`) performs call-graph analysis — it only flags vulnerabilities in code paths your binary actually executes, eliminating noise from unused transitive deps.

Pin a dependency to a specific version with `go get github.com/some/pkg@v1.4.2`, or upgrade all minor/patch versions with `go get -u ./...`. Use `go mod why github.com/some/pkg` to trace exactly why a transitive dependency exists in your graph.$escape$,
  $escape$# Tidy and verify the module graph
go mod tidy
go mod verify

# Pin a specific version
go get github.com/some/pkg@v1.4.2

# Upgrade all dependencies (minor/patch only)
go get -u ./...

# Audit for vulnerabilities (call-graph aware)
govulncheck ./...

# Trace why a transitive dep exists
go mod why golang.org/x/text$escape$,
