INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '32bbcafc-1bcc-4d36-b2f9-f03e38144520',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Go's Concurrency Model — Goroutines, Channels, and the sync Package$escape$,
  $escape$Go's concurrency is built on goroutines — lightweight, multiplexed onto OS threads by the Go runtime's M:N scheduler. Unlike async/await (cooperative, single-threaded) or Java threads (1:1, expensive), goroutines cost ~2KB of stack initially and the runtime handles preemption automatically since Go 1.14.

Communication follows the CSP model: goroutines share data by communicating over channels rather than sharing memory with locks. A `chan` is typed, directional, and blocks naturally — no callbacks, no futures. Buffered channels (`make(chan T, n)`) decouple send and receive; unbuffered channels synchronize.

When you need shared state, `sync.Mutex` and `sync.RWMutex` are idiomatic. `sync.WaitGroup` coordinates fan-out. `sync/atomic` handles counters without locks. The `context.Context` pattern propagates cancellation across goroutine trees — critical for timeouts in HTTP handlers or gRPC calls.

Go's race detector (`go test -race`) is a first-class tool — run it always. The scheduler's work-stealing algorithm keeps GOMAXPROCS threads busy, so CPU-bound goroutines parallelize without extra configuration.$escape$,
  $escape$func fanOut(jobs []string) []string {
	results := make(chan string, len(jobs))
	var wg sync.WaitGroup

	for _, job := range jobs {
		wg.Add(1)
		go func(j string) {
			defer wg.Done()
			results <- process(j)
		}(job)
	}

	wg.Wait()
	close(results)

	out := make([]string, 0, len(jobs))
	for r := range results {
		out = append(out, r)
	}
	return out
}$escape$,
  $escape$go$escape$,
