INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '04508c7f-5349-48cc-822d-f14a1f9433af',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Go's Type System — Static Safety, Inference, and Generics Without the Ceremony$escape$,
  $escape$Go is statically typed: every variable has a type known at compile time, eliminating entire classes of runtime bugs. The compiler rejects mismatched types — no implicit coercion like JavaScript, no silent int-to-float widening. Yet Go avoids verbosity through type inference: `:=` lets the compiler deduce the type from the right-hand side, so `count := 0` is `int`, `ratio := 0.5` is `float64`, no annotation needed.

Before Go 1.18, writing reusable data structures meant `interface{}` — you'd lose type safety and litter code with type assertions. Generics changed this. Type parameters with constraints (via `interface`) let you write functions and types that work across concrete types while the compiler still enforces correctness at each call site. The `comparable` constraint enables generic maps and sets; `constraints.Ordered` (from `golang.org/x/exp`) enables sorting. Unlike Java's erasure, Go generics generate specialized code per type set, so no boxing overhead. The result: safety at compile time, flexibility without reflection, and zero runtime cost.$escape$,
  $escape$package main

import "fmt"

// Generic Min — works for any ordered type
func Min[T int | float64 | string](a, b T) T {
	if a < b {
		return a
	}
	return b
}

func main() {
	fmt.Println(Min(3, 7))       // int: 3
	fmt.Println(Min(1.2, 0.8))   // float64: 0.8
	fmt.Println(Min("go", "rust")) // string: go
}$escape$,
  $escape$go$escape$,
