INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0941cbed-7c52-49dc-a3d4-546f48d24b19',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Go's GC vs Stack Allocation — How the Escape Analyzer Decides Your Memory Model$escape$,
  $escape$Go doesn't give you manual memory control, but understanding escape analysis lets you write GC-friendly code. The compiler decides at build time whether a variable lives on the goroutine stack or the heap. Stack allocation is free — no GC pressure, no scanning. Heap allocation triggers the tricolor mark-sweep GC, which causes stop-the-world pauses (though microsecond-scale in modern Go).

Run `go build -gcflags='-m'` to see escape decisions. A value escapes to heap when its address outlives the function — returning a pointer, storing into an interface, or passing to a goroutine are common causes. Interfaces are particularly sneaky: assigning a concrete type to an interface almost always causes a heap allocation because the runtime needs a fat pointer (type + data).

Go has no ownership model like Rust. Safety comes from the GC — use-after-free and dangling pointers are impossible by design. The tradeoff is latency unpredictability under allocation pressure. Use `sync.Pool` to recycle short-lived objects and reduce GC churn in hot paths. Profile with `runtime/pprof` or `go tool pprof` before optimizing — escape analysis output tells you where, pprof tells you whether it matters.$escape$,
  $escape$package main

import "fmt"

// stays on stack — does not escape
func stackAlloc() int {
	x := 42
	return x
}

// escapes to heap — address returned
func heapAlloc() *int {
	x := 42
	return &x
}

func main() {
	// go build -gcflags='-m' ./... to verify escape decisions
	fmt.Println(stackAlloc())
	fmt.Println(*heapAlloc())
}$escape$,
  $escape$go$escape$,
