INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ae44ce99-a82c-455f-8488-7d151c238793',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Go Security — Memory Safety, Injection Prevention, and govulncheck$escape$,
  $escape$Go eliminates entire vulnerability classes present in C/C++ at the language level — no manual malloc/free means no use-after-free or heap corruption. The runtime enforces bounds checking on slice and array access, panicking rather than silently overwriting memory.

For injection prevention, the cardinal rule: never use fmt.Sprintf to build SQL strings. Use database/sql's parameterized queries — the driver handles escaping at the protocol level, not in userspace. For HTML output, always reach for html/template over text/template; its context-aware auto-escaping prevents XSS by treating data and code as separate concerns by design.

For dependency vulnerability scanning, the Go team ships govulncheck (golang.org/x/vuln/cmd/govulncheck), which queries the Go Vulnerability Database at vuln.go.dev. Its key advantage over generic scanners: reachability analysis. It only reports CVEs in code paths your compiled binary actually exercises, cutting noise dramatically. Run `govulncheck ./...` in CI on every push. Supplement with go mod tidy and Renovate for automated upgrades. The go.sum file provides cryptographic integrity verification of every module, making supply-chain tampering detectable at build time.$escape$,
  $escape$// UNSAFE: direct string interpolation — never do this
query := fmt.Sprintf("SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = '%s'", email)

// SAFE: parameterized query via database/sql
row := db.QueryRowContext(ctx,
	"SELECT id, name FROM users WHERE email = $1",
	email,
)
var id int
var name string
if err := row.Scan(&id, &name); err != nil {
	return nil, err
}$escape$,
  $escape$go$escape$,
