INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a358da7f-837f-490f-9dd6-060ae52519b8',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Go Dev Tooling — REPL, Delve Debugger, and gopls LSP in Practice$escape$,
  $escape$Go lacks a built-in REPL, but `gore` fills that gap cleanly. Install with `go install github.com/x-motemen/gore/cmd/gore@latest` and run `gore` to get an interactive session with tab-completion and import support — ideal for quickly validating interface behavior or testing stdlib edge cases.

For debugging, `dlv` (Delve) is the standard. Run `dlv debug ./cmd/server` to compile and attach in one step. Use `break main.handleRequest`, `continue`, `print req.Header`, and `goroutines` to inspect all live goroutines — critical for diagnosing deadlocks. `dlv test` lets you set breakpoints inside test functions without modifying any code.

The language server `gopls` powers IDE features across VS Code, Neovim, and GoLand. It handles inlay hints, rename refactoring, and `go/analysis`-based diagnostics in real time. Configure workspace-level settings via `gopls.env` in your editor config — especially useful for setting `GOFLAGS=-mod=vendor` in monorepos. Run `gopls check ./...` from the CLI to surface diagnostics outside the editor.$escape$,
  $escape$# Install tooling
go install github.com/x-motemen/gore/cmd/gore@latest
go install github.com/go-delve/delve/cmd/dlv@latest
go install golang.org/x/tools/gopls@latest

# Interactive REPL session
gore

# Debug a specific package entrypoint
dlv debug ./cmd/api

# Inside dlv: set breakpoint, run, inspect goroutines
# (dlv) break main.handleRequest
# (dlv) continue
# (dlv) goroutines

# Debug only failing tests
dlv test ./internal/auth -- -run TestTokenExpiry$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
